[2
Date: 16 Jun 2001
From: Chris Griot <griot@freesurf.ch>
Source: Reuters, 14 Jun 2001 [edited

On Thursday [14 Jun 2001, the European Commission said it banned live pig
exports from Spain's Catalonia region due to an outbreak of classical swine
fever (CSF) there. The Commission said it was informed earlier on Thursday
of the outbreak and the Spanish authorities had imposed a 3km protection
zone and a 10km surveillance zone around one infected farm.
"The Commission services are in close and permanent contact with the
Spanish authorities and have been kept fully informed of developments," it
said in a statement.
CSF is a highly infectious pig virus and although nearly always fatal to
the animals it is not harmful to people.
It said the ban would last until 30 Jun and a special meeting of the EU's
Standing Veterinary Committee would review the situation further at a
meeting on 22 Jun.
The Commission said, according to information provided by Spain, no animals
had left the holding, except for slaughter, since 14 May and a census of
all holdings in both zones would be carried out.
Spain's Ministry of Agriculture has also said the 2053 pigs on the farm in
the province of Llieda would be killed.
Spain had its last major outbreak of CSF in 1998 when hundreds of thousands
of pigs were slaughtered to prevent the disease from spreading.
